[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":128},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F":104,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F":113},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190516\u002F2522156098\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":86,"date":87,"description":88,"extension":89,"lang":90,"meta":91,"navigation":92,"path":93,"readingMinutes":94,"seo":95,"standalone":96,"stem":97,"tags":98,"tldr":101,"updated":87,"url":102,"__hash__":103},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let.md","[JS Weird World] No.11 Scope, ES6, and let","1000015841",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":80},"minimark",[11,16,23,26,50,67,71],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"scope","Scope",[17,18,19],"p",{},[20,21],"img",{"alt":15,"src":22},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FzcFXFNPh.png",[17,24,25],{},"Scope basically means the area where a variable can be accessed.",[17,27,28,29,33,34,36,37,40,41,43,44,46,47,49],{},"The reason it's worth calling out in this chapter is that ES6 introduced a pretty special keyword — ",[30,31,32],"code",{},"let",". You can use ",[30,35,32],{}," a lot like ",[30,38,39],{},"var","; it's just another way to create a variable. But ",[30,42,32],{}," didn't replace ",[30,45,39],{},", so ",[30,48,39],{}," is still around and still works.",[17,51,52,53,55,56,60,61,63,64,66],{},"Here's the key thing though: ",[30,54,32],{}," makes the JavaScript engine use something called ",[57,58,59],"strong",{},"block scope",". So what's ",[57,62,59],{},"? A block is generally defined as whatever's inside curly braces. There's more to come on this later — for now, you just need to know that ",[30,65,32],{}," exists.",[12,68,70],{"id":69},"image-source","Image source",[17,72,73],{},[74,75,79],"a",{"href":76,"rel":77},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[78],"nofollow","JavaScript Full Course: Conquering the Weird Parts (course in Mandarin)",{"title":81,"searchDepth":82,"depth":82,"links":83},"",2,[84,85],{"id":14,"depth":82,"text":15},{"id":69,"depth":82,"text":70},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-16 14:30:35","Scope is basically the area where a variable can be accessed. In this part we look at ES6's new keyword let — how it works like var, why it didn't replace var, and the block scope idea it brings to the table.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let","1",{"title":6,"description":88},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let",[99,100],"JavaScript","JavaScript Full Course: Conquering the Weird Parts",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjsweirdworld-11-scope-es6-let\u002F","xLhHCYKkge2NIrAvsfZWD3EAtv-x9si-IRqpBC1Sh6M",{"newer":105,"older":109},{"url":106,"title":107,"date":108},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-12-async-callbacks\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.12 How Async Callbacks Actually Work","2019-05-16 15:30:35",{"url":110,"title":111,"date":112},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F16\u002Fjs-weird-world-10-scope-chain\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.10 The Scope Chain","2019-05-16 14:00:35",[114,119,123],{"url":115,"title":116,"date":117,"readingMinutes":118},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":120,"title":121,"date":122,"readingMinutes":94},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] N